Japan, India, Malaysia, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-02-27T22:00:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-27/japan-india-malaysia-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will have media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry will release at
8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its preliminary data on industrial production
in January. Japan’s industrial output rose 4 percent in January
from December, when it increased 3.3 percent, according to a
Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The Trade Ministry will publish at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on retail sales in January. Sales at Japanese retailers
rose 2.7 percent in January from December, when they fell a
revised 4.2 percent, a separate Bloomberg survey showed.  The Shoko Chukin Bank will release at 10 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on confidence among small businesses for February.  The yield on the 1.2 percent government bond due December
2020 was at 1.24 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.69 per dollar at 6:35 a.m. in Tokyo.    India : Finance Minister Pranab Mukherjee will unveil the
budget for the next fiscal year starting April 1.  Gross domestic product grew 8.6 percent in the three months
ended Dec. 31  from a year earlier, compared with a gain of 8.9
percent in the previous quarter, according to a survey of
economists by Bloomberg News before official data today.  The yield on the benchmark 7.8 percent bond due May 2020
was 8.08 percent. The rupee was at 45.325.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell a combined 4 billion
ringgit ($1.3 billion) of 128-day and 210-day notes. It will
also auction 1 billion ringgit of 91-day Islamic securities.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.44 percent. The ringgit was at 3.05.    Singapore : The government will sell S$3.9 billion ($3
billion) of 91-day Treasury bills.  The yield on 3.25 percent note due September 2020 was at
2.59 percent. The  Singapore dollar  traded at S$1.2734.    South Korea : Manufacturers’ confidence rose to a five-month
high as an economic recovery improved the sales outlook for the
month of March. The manufacturers’ confidence index jumped to 96
from 91 in February, the  Bank of Korea  said in a statement in  Seoul  today. A measure of non-manufacturing companies’
expectations rose to 85 from 84.  The government will sell 1 trillion won ($887 million) of
20-year bonds.  The yield on the 5 percent debt due June 2020 was 4.65
percent. The won was at 1,126.45 per dollar.    Thailand : The current-account surplus shrank to $125
million in January from $1.75 billion in December, a Bloomberg
News survey of economists before a report today.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.44 percent. The baht was at 30.62.  To contact the reporter on this story:
